  "prompt": "Who discovered Avogadro's number?",
  "response": "Avogadro's number, approximately \\(6.022 \\times 10^{23}\\), represents the number of constituent particles (such as atoms or molecules) in one mole of a substance. While the concept is named after the Italian scientist **Amedeo Avogadro**, who proposed the foundational hypothesis in 1811 that equal volumes of gases, at the same temperature and pressure, contain the same number of particles, he did not determine the numerical value of the constant.\n\nThe precise determination of Avogadro's number was achieved through the work of several scientists over the years:\n\n1. **Jean Perrin**: A French physicist, Perrin is often credited with the first accurate experimental determination of Avogadro's number in the early 20th century. He used observations of Brownian motion and statistical mechanics to estimate the number, for which he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1926.\n\n2. **Other Contributors**:\n    - **Robert Millikan**: Known for his oil drop experiment, Millikan provided measurements of the elementary electric charge, which, when combined with other constants, helped in calculating Avogadro's number.\n    - **Johann Josef Loschmidt**: In the 19th century, Loschmidt estimated the number of particles in a given volume of gas (known as Loschmidt's number), which is related to Avogadro's number.\n    - **Alexander Graham Bell and Walter Nernst**: Their work in physical chemistry and thermodynamics also contributed to refining the value of Avogadro's number.\n\nToday, Avogadro's number is determined with high precision using various methods, including X-ray crystallography and measurements involving the Planck constant. The collaborative efforts of these and other scientists over time have led to the accurate value we use in chemistry and physics today.\n\nIn summary, while **Amedeo Avogadro** provided the theoretical foundation, **Jean Perrin** is primarily recognized for the experimental determination of Avogadro's number.",
